The Jacobian conjecture is famously disproved by an explicit polynomial counterexample in 3 dimensions. The map takes distinct inputs to the exact same output, meaning it is not globally injective and cannot be inverted. [1, 2]  
For the polynomial mapping $F: \mathbb{C}^3 \rightarrow \mathbb{C}^3$ defined by components (f₁, f₂, f₃): 

• f₁ = (1+xy)³ z + y²(1+xy)(4+3xy) 
• f₂ = y + 3x(1+xy)² z + 3xy²(4+3xy) 
• f₃ = 2x - 3x²y - x³z 

This function has a constant Jacobian determinant of -2, satisfying the initial criteria of the conjecture, but distinct inputs collapse to the same image. [1, 2]  
For further reading on the derivation and algebraic geometry underlying the equations, you can explore the Wikipedia Jacobian Conjecture page or review the detailed ulam.ai Research Paper outlining the map's properties. [1]  
